Implementation Plan — Production-Level LangSmith Evaluation for IRCTC AI Agent
Problem Statement
You have a LangGraph agent with full LangSmith tracing but zero structured evaluation. The goal is to build a complete, mentor-impressive eval pipeline: dataset creation from real traces → local evaluation with heuristic + LLM-as-judge scorers → experiment tracking in LangSmith → prompt versioning via Hub.

Requirements
What to evaluate: tool selection accuracy, slot-filling correctness, response quality, reflection node behavior, routing correctness, and end-to-end booking/cancellation flows
Dataset source: export real traces from LangSmith UI as ground truth, supplemented by manually curated edge cases
Evaluators: heuristic/deterministic for structural checks (tool name, required args), LLM-as-judge for quality/coherence — both run locally
Experiment tracking: every eval run pushed back to LangSmith as a named experiment with metadata (model version, prompt version, date)
Prompt versioning: prompts live as local versioned YAML files (git-tracked) and are pushed to LangSmith Hub; each experiment is tagged with the prompt version
Run scope: per-intent datasets that compose into a full regression suite
Delivery format: Python scripts (one command = full eval run), plus a Makefile for convenience
Background
From reading your codebase:

langsmith>=0.2.0 is already installed and tracing is wired in lifespan.py
The OpenAI client is already wrapped with wrap_openai() — all LLM calls are traced automatically
agent_node.py has _SYSTEM_TEMPLATE hardcoded inline — this needs extraction into versioned prompt files
reflection_node.py uses a separate _REFLECT_SYSTEM prompt also hardcoded
You have 4 unit tests covering tool_meta, ranking, reflection, preferences — eval builds on top of these
The TravelState fields (tool_history, pending_tool_calls, errors, search_results, booking) are rich enough to derive all eval metrics without any extra instrumentation
LangSmith's evaluate() API takes a dataset name + a target function + a list of evaluators and handles experiment creation automatically
Proposed Solution
A layered eval system with three levels:


┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                    DATASET LAYER                                │
│  LangSmith UI → Export traces → Curate into typed datasets      │
│  Per-intent: search / booking / cancel / slot_fill / reflection │
└────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────────┘
                         │
┌────────────────────────▼────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                   EVALUATOR LAYER                               │
│                                                                 │
│  Heuristic Evaluators (no LLM cost, deterministic):            │
│  ├─ tool_called_correctly   (exact tool name match)            │
│  ├─ required_args_present   (all required slots non-null)      │
│  ├─ no_hallucinated_pnr     (PNR in output = PNR in tool data) │
│  ├─ routing_correct         (destructive → approval node)      │
│  └─ reflection_verdict_valid (reflection only fires when needed)│
│                                                                 │
│  LLM-as-Judge Evaluators (GPT-4o, structured output):          │
│  ├─ response_helpfulness    (1–5 Likert)                       │
│  ├─ response_groundedness   (no invented facts)                │
│  ├─ slot_filling_quality    (multi-turn coherence)             │
│  └─ tone_and_clarity        (concise, professional, no halluc) │
└────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────────┘
                         │
┌────────────────────────▼────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                  EXPERIMENT LAYER                               │
│                                                                 │
│  eval/run_eval.py                                               │
│  ├─ Fetches dataset from LangSmith                             │
│  ├─ Runs target function (mock or live agent)                  │
│  ├─ Applies all evaluators                                     │
│  ├─ Tags experiment: {prompt_version, model, date}             │
│  └─ Pushes results to LangSmith Experiments tab                │
│                                                                 │
│  eval/prompts/ (YAML, git-versioned)                           │
│  ├─ agent_system_prompt_v1.yaml                                │
│  ├─ agent_system_prompt_v2.yaml                                │
│  └─ reflection_system_prompt_v1.yaml                           │
│  + pushed to LangSmith Hub for UI comparison                   │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
Dataset Schema Design
Each dataset example follows this structure so it works for both single-turn and multi-turn eval:

python

# Input (what goes into the agent)
{
    "input": "Book a ticket from Delhi to Mumbai tomorrow in 3A",
    "conversation_history": [],          # list of prior turns for multi-turn cases
    "user_email": "test@example.com",
    "context": {                          # pre-loaded state (simulates prior tool calls)
        "search_results": [...],
        "selected_train": {...}
    }
}

# Reference output (ground truth from your traces)
{
    "expected_tool": "book_ticket",       # or list for multi-tool turns
    "expected_args_subset": {             # args that MUST be present (not exhaustive)
        "trainNumber": "12951",
        "travelClass": "3A"
    },
    "expected_response_contains": ["PNR", "confirmed"],  # keywords in final answer
    "should_route_to_approval": True,     # did it correctly hit human_approval_node?
    "expected_intent": "book_ticket"
}
Task Breakdown
Task 1: Prompt Extraction — Move Hardcoded Prompts to Versioned YAML Files

Objective: Extract _SYSTEM_TEMPLATE from agent_node.py and _REFLECT_SYSTEM from reflection_node.py into version-controlled YAML files under eval/prompts/. Wire a PromptRegistry that loads them. This is the foundation for prompt versioning.

Implementation guidance:

Create 
agent_system_v1.yaml
 — store the full _SYSTEM_TEMPLATE as a YAML string field with metadata: version, description, model, created_at
Create 
reflection_system_v1.yaml
 — same for _REFLECT_SYSTEM
Create 
prompt_registry.py
 with:
load_prompt(name: str, version: str) -> str — reads YAML from eval/prompts/
push_to_hub(name: str, version: str) — pushes to LangSmith Hub via langsmith.Client().push_prompt()
CURRENT_AGENT_PROMPT_VERSION = "v1" — single place to bump version
Keep _SYSTEM_TEMPLATE in agent_node.py as a fallback for backward compatibility — PromptRegistry is used in eval, the node can optionally call it
Push both prompts to LangSmith Hub so they appear in the UI
Test requirements:

test_prompt_registry.py: assert YAML loads correctly, version field is present, template format strings ({today}, {context}, {feedback}) are preserved
Demo: Run python -c "from eval.prompt_registry import load_prompt; print(load_prompt('agent_system', 'v1')[:100])" and see the prompt. Open LangSmith Hub in the browser and see the prompt appear there.

Task 2: Dataset Schema + Seed Datasets — 5 Intent-Specific Datasets

Objective: Create typed dataset examples for 5 intents and upload them to LangSmith, ready for evaluation. These are manually curated but modeled on your real traces.

Implementation guidance:

Create eval/datasets/ directory with one JSON file per intent:
train_search.json — 8 examples: simple search, search with class preference, search with date expression ("tomorrow"), multi-city ambiguity
booking_flow.json — 6 examples: full booking with all slots, partial slots (slot-filling), use saved passenger, re-confirm after decline
cancellation_flow.json — 5 examples: cancel by PNR, cancel most recent booking, cancel non-existent PNR, cancel after decline
slot_filling_multiturn.json — 6 examples: multi-turn conversations where slots arrive one per turn (represented as conversation_history arrays)
reflection_quality.json — 5 examples: tool succeeded but answer incomplete, tool failed, answer contradicts data
Create 
upload_datasets.py
:
Uses langsmith.Client().create_dataset() and client.create_examples()
Is idempotent — checks if dataset already exists before creating
Each example has inputs and outputs keys matching the schema above
Tags each dataset with irctc_agent and the intent name
Test requirements:

test_dataset_schema.py: load each JSON file, assert all required keys present, assert expected_tool is a valid MCP tool name (cross-reference against _TOOL_REQUIRED_SLOTS in agent_node.py)
Demo: Run python eval/upload_datasets.py → open LangSmith UI → see 5 datasets each with correct number of examples and proper tags.

Task 3: Heuristic Evaluators — Deterministic, Zero LLM Cost

Objective: Build 5 deterministic evaluators that check structural correctness of agent outputs. These run in milliseconds, cost nothing, and give you hard pass/fail signals.

Implementation guidance:

Create 
heuristic.py
 with these evaluator functions. Each takes (run, example) and returns {"key": "...", "score": 0 or 1, "comment": "..."}:
tool_called_correctly(run, example) — checks run.outputs["tool_calls"][0]["name"] == example.outputs["expected_tool"]
required_args_present(run, example) — verifies all keys in expected_args_subset exist and are non-null in the actual tool call args
no_hallucinated_pnr(run, example) — extracts all 10-digit numbers from run.outputs["response"], checks each against run.outputs["tool_results"] (mirrors _ground_reply logic in agent_node.py)
routing_correct(run, example) — if example.outputs["should_route_to_approval"] is True, checks that run.outputs["interrupted"] is True
no_error_in_output(run, example) — checks run.outputs["errors"] is empty
Create 
__init__.py
 to export all evaluators as a HEURISTIC_EVALUATORS list
Test requirements:

test_heuristic_evaluators.py: for each evaluator, test the True case (should pass) and False case (should fail) using mock run and example objects (plain dataclasses, no LangSmith needed)
Demo: Run pytest tests/eval/test_heuristic_evaluators.py -v — see 10 green tests, no network calls.

Task 4: LLM-as-Judge Evaluators — Quality Scoring

Objective: Build 4 LLM-based evaluators using GPT-4o with structured output (JSON schema enforced) for quality dimensions that rules can't capture.

Implementation guidance:

Create 
llm_judge.py
:
Base helper _judge(prompt: str, schema: dict) -> dict — calls OpenAI with response_format={"type": "json_schema", ...}, temperature=0, max_tokens=200
response_helpfulness(run, example) — score 1–5: "Does this response fully answer the user's travel question? Score 1=not at all, 5=completely." Returns {"key": "helpfulness", "score": score/5} (normalized to 0–1)
response_groundedness(run, example) — binary: "Does the response contain any facts (fares, PNRs, seat counts) not present in the tool results?" Returns {"key": "groundedness", "score": 1 if grounded else 0}
slot_filling_quality(run, example) — score 0–1: "In a multi-turn booking flow, did the agent ask for exactly one missing field at a time without re-asking for already-collected fields?"
tone_and_clarity(run, example) — score 0–1: "Is the response concise, professional, and free of filler phrases like 'Certainly!' or 'Great question!'?"
Each evaluator catches exceptions and returns score=0.5 (neutral) on failure — eval must never crash
Add LLM_JUDGE_EVALUATORS list to 
__init__.py
Test requirements:

test_llm_judge_evaluators.py: mock the OpenAI client, assert each evaluator returns the right key name, score is between 0 and 1, exception is handled gracefully
Demo: Call one evaluator directly on a hardcoded example: python -c "from eval.evaluators.llm_judge import response_helpfulness; ..." and see a score + comment printed.

Task 5: Target Function — Agent Wrapper for Eval

Objective: Build a lightweight target function that takes a dataset input dict and returns the output dict that evaluators read. This runs your actual agent graph (or a mock for offline eval) and normalizes the output.

Implementation guidance:

Create 
target.py
:
async def run_agent(inputs: dict) -> dict — instantiates a minimal version of your agent (no FastAPI, no Socket.IO, no MongoDB — just the graph + a mock MCP registry that returns fixture data)
Returns a normalized dict:
python

{
    "response": str,              # final AIMessage content
    "tool_calls": list,           # all tool calls made this run
    "tool_results": list,         # all tool results
    "errors": list,               # from state["errors"]
    "interrupted": bool,          # True if graph hit human_approval interrupt
    "routing_path": list[str],    # node names visited in order
    "prompt_version": str,        # from PromptRegistry.CURRENT_VERSION
    "model": str,                 # from settings
}
MockMCPRegistry — returns fixture JSON responses for each tool, loaded from eval/fixtures/ directory. This makes eval reproducible and offline
sync_run_agent(inputs: dict) -> dict — sync wrapper using asyncio.run() for use with LangSmith's evaluate() which expects sync callables
Test requirements:

test_target.py: run sync_run_agent with a train search input + mock MCP, assert output dict has all required keys, assert tool_calls[0]["name"] == "search_trains" or "find_station"
Demo: python -c "from eval.target import sync_run_agent; import json; print(json.dumps(sync_run_agent({'input': 'Find trains from Delhi to Mumbai tomorrow', 'user_email': 'test@test.com', 'conversation_history': [], 'context': {}}), indent=2))" — see the full agent output dict.

Task 6: Eval Runner — Full Pipeline Script

Objective: Wire everything together into a single 
run_eval.py
 script that fetches a dataset, runs the target, applies all evaluators, and pushes a named experiment to LangSmith.

Implementation guidance:

Create 
run_eval.py
:
python

# Usage: python eval/run_eval.py --dataset booking_flow --suite heuristic
# python eval/run_eval.py --dataset all --suite full
Uses langsmith.evaluate() (the high-level API) — it handles batching, error isolation per example, and experiment creation automatically
Experiment name format: irctc-{dataset}-{prompt_version}-{model}-{YYYYMMDD} e.g. irctc-booking_flow-v1-gpt4o-mini-20250718
Passes metadata={"prompt_version": ..., "model": ..., "git_commit": subprocess.check_output(["git", "rev-parse", "--short", "HEAD"]).decode().strip()} so every experiment is fully traceable
--suite heuristic runs only heuristic evaluators (cheap, fast), --suite full runs all including LLM judges
--dataset all runs all 5 datasets in sequence and prints a summary table
Create 
compare_experiments.py
:
Fetches the last N experiment results for a dataset via langsmith.Client().list_runs()
Prints a terminal table showing score delta between experiments — so you can instantly see if a prompt change improved or degraded things
Test requirements:

test_run_eval.py: mock langsmith.evaluate(), assert it's called with correct dataset name, evaluators list, and metadata keys
Demo: Run python eval/run_eval.py --dataset train_search --suite heuristic — see a progress bar, then open LangSmith → Experiments tab → see a new experiment named irctc-train_search-v1-gpt4o-mini-<date> with per-example scores and aggregate metrics.

Task 7: Prompt Versioning A/B — Compare v1 vs v2 Experiment

Objective: Create a second version of the agent system prompt with a specific improvement, run evals for both versions, and demonstrate score comparison in LangSmith. This is the piece that will genuinely impress your mentor.

Implementation guidance:

Create 
agent_system_v2.yaml
 — a modified version of v1 with one concrete improvement: tighten the SLOT-FILLING PROTOCOL section to be more explicit about berth preference ordering (common failure case from your traces)
Update PromptRegistry.CURRENT_AGENT_PROMPT_VERSION = "v2" in one place
Push v2 to LangSmith Hub: langsmith.Client().push_prompt("irctc-agent-system", object=v2_prompt, tags=["v2"])
Run the full eval suite twice: once with v1 (revert the constant), once with v2 — this produces two experiments with different prompt_version metadata
Add a Makefile with targets:
makefile

eval-quick:      ## Run heuristic eval on all datasets
    python eval/run_eval.py --dataset all --suite heuristic

eval-full:       ## Run full eval (heuristic + LLM judge) on all datasets
    python eval/run_eval.py --dataset all --suite full

eval-compare:    ## Print score delta between last 2 experiments
    python eval/compare_experiments.py --dataset all --n 2

prompts-push:    ## Push all prompt versions to LangSmith Hub
    python eval/prompt_registry.py push-all

upload-datasets: ## Upload/refresh datasets to LangSmith
    python eval/upload_datasets.py
Test requirements:

test_prompt_v2.py: load v2 YAML, assert it differs from v1, assert all required format keys still present, assert version field is "v2"
Demo: Run make eval-compare — terminal shows a table like:


Dataset          | Metric                  | v1     | v2     | Delta
booking_flow     | tool_called_correctly   | 0.83   | 0.92   | +0.09 ✅
booking_flow     | slot_filling_quality    | 0.71   | 0.85   | +0.14 ✅
Open LangSmith → Experiments tab → select both experiments → click "Compare" → see side-by-side score visualization.

Task 8: Trace-to-Dataset Export — Bootstrap Datasets from Real Traces

Objective: Build a utility that pulls your existing LangSmith traces and converts them into dataset examples automatically. This closes the loop — real production behavior becomes your eval ground truth.

Implementation guidance:

Create 
export_traces.py
:
fetch_traces(project: str, intent_filter: str, limit: int) -> list — uses langsmith.Client().list_runs(project_name=project, filter=f'eq(metadata_key("intent"), "{intent_filter}")', limit=limit)
trace_to_example(run) -> dict — maps a LangSmith run to the dataset input/output schema:
Extracts the first HumanMessage as inputs["input"]
Extracts all tool calls made as outputs["expected_tool"]
Extracts final AIMessage as outputs["expected_response"]
Flags outputs["should_route_to_approval"] if any destructive tool appears in the trace
export_to_dataset(intent: str, limit: int = 20) — runs the above and calls upload_datasets.py logic to upsert into the LangSmith dataset
Add a CLI: python eval/export_traces.py --intent book_ticket --limit 20
Test requirements:

test_export_traces.py: mock Client().list_runs(), assert trace_to_example() extracts correct fields, assert destructive tool detection works
Demo: Run python eval/export_traces.py --intent search_trains --limit 10 — see "Exported 10 examples to dataset irctc-train_search" printed. Open LangSmith datasets → see new examples appended from real traces.

